g.text: X-Ray
Concepts
1. Trace: Think of trace as the entire journey of a request in your application.
Analogy: A trace is like the whole delivery trip of a package. Order placed to delivered everything is tracked.
Example: User req data from API. The trace captures the entire journey of that request, time it takes, services it interacted with (db or APIs)
2. Segment: A segment is a piece of the journey representing what happens within one part of your application
(example: your API or database).
Analogy: A segment is like one part of delivery process. For example when the package leaves the warehouse or when it's handed to the delivery agent.
Example: If a user requests a list of products from your API, the segment might represent the time spent processing the request in you application's backend.
This segment includes information like how long it took to execute the request and what services were called.
3. Subsegment: A subsegment represents even smaller parts of a segment, breaking down specific task
or call within the application.
Analogy: A subsegment is like a detailed step within a part of the delivery process. For instance, the time it took to load the package onto the truck
or to scan it at a checkpoint.
Example: Inside the segment where your backend fetches data from a database, the subsegment could track how long it takes to query the database,
what specific query was made, and whether it was successful.
4. Sampling: Controls how many requests are traced. If you get too many requests, X-Ray doesn't trace every
single one to avoid overload. (decrease the amount or request, reduce cost)
Example: If your API gets 1000 requests per seconds, AWS X-Ray might trace only 1% of them (10 requests). This way, you don;t have too much data
to process but still get a clear picture of the system's performance.
4. Annotations: It is like label or tag you add to your trace data. It helps you search and filter traces later.
(key-value pairs)
Example: You can add an annotation to trace that says userType: "premium" so later, you can filter traces.
5. Metadata: It is a additional information you can include in traces to give more detail. (key-value pairs)
(Not used for searching)
Example: You can add an annotation to trace that says userType: "premium" so later, you can filter traces.
